:::summary
Desiderius Erasmus of Rotterdam (c. 1466–1536) was the greatest Christian humanist of the Renaissance — a Dutch scholar, theologian, and satirist whose immense learning, devastating wit, and reformist piety shaped the intellectual landscape of 16th-century Europe. His critical edition of the Greek New Testament set the standard for biblical scholarship; his *In Praise of Folly* was the most brilliant satire of its age; and his vision of a Christianity purified by learning and genuine piety placed him at the center of every major controversy of the Reformation era — though he ultimately refused to break with the Catholic Church. The phrase "Erasmus laid the egg that Luther hatched" captures how thoroughly his reformist scholarship prepared the way for the Protestant Reformation, even though he himself opposed Luther's schism.
:::

